{"timestamp": "2025-12-11 18:50:25.971665", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: I’m sorry to hear you’re having trouble connecting to the internet. Let’s see if we can narrow it down and get you back online. \\n\\n---\\n\\n### 1. Quick Check: Is the problem DNS‑related?\\n\\n**What to look for:**\\n- **Can you ping an IP address?**  \\n  Open a terminal or command prompt and try:  \\n  ```bash\\n  ping 8.8.8.8\\n  ```  \\n  If you get replies, your network connection is working but DNS might be the issue.\\n\\n- **Can you ping a domain name?**  \\n  ```bash\\n  ping www.google.com\\n  ```  \\n  If this fails while the IP ping works, it’s almost certainly a DNS problem.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 2. Basic Troubleshooting Steps\\n\\n| Step | What to Do | Why It Helps |\\n|------|------------|--------------|\\n| **Restart your router/modem** | Power cycle the device. | Clears temporary glitches. |\\n| **Check your DNS settings** | Go to your network adapter settings and see which DNS servers are listed. | Wrong or unreachable DNS servers can block name resolution. |\\n| **Try a public DNS** | Temporarily set your DNS to 8.8.8.8 (Google) or 1.1.1.1 (Cloudflare). | If this fixes the issue, your ISP’s DNS is likely the culprit. |\\n| **Flush DNS cache** | `ipconfig /flushdns` (Windows) or `sudo dscacheutil -flushcache; sudo killall -HUP mDNSResponder` (macOS). | Removes stale DNS entries. |\\n| **Check firewall/antivirus** | Disable temporarily to see if it’s blocking DNS. | Some security software can interfere with DNS queries. |\\n| **Check for IP conflicts** | Run `ipconfig /all` (Windows) or `ifconfig` (Linux/macOS) to see if you have a duplicate IP. | IP conflicts can cause connectivity issues. |\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 3. If the Problem Persists\\n\\n#### A. Verify Your Network Configuration\\n\\n1. **Static vs. DHCP**  \\n   - If you’re using a static IP, double‑check the gateway, subnet mask, and DNS entries.  \\n   - If you’re on DHCP, try renewing the lease:  \\n     ```bash\\n     ipconfig /release\\n     ipconfig /renew\\n     ```\\n\\n2. **Check the Gateway**  \\n   - Ping your router’s IP (usually 192.168.1.1 or 10.0.0.1).  \\n   - If you can’t ping the gateway, the issue is likely local (cable, Wi‑Fi, or router).\\n\\n#### B. Test with a Different Device\\n\\n- If another device on the same network can access the internet, the problem is specific to your machine.  \\n- If no device works, the issue is likely with the router or ISP.\\n\\n#### C. Look at the Router’s Logs\\n\\n- Log into your router’s admin interface and check for any error messages or blocked connections.  \\n- Some routers have a “DNS” section where you can set custom DNS servers.\\n\\n#### D. Contact Your ISP\\n\\n- If all else fails, your ISP might be experiencing outages or DNS server issues.  \\n- Provide them with the results of the tests above (e.g., “I can ping 8.8.8.8 but not www.google.com”).\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 4. Quick Fix: Using a Public DNS\\n\\nIf you suspect a DNS issue, here’s a quick way to test it:\\n\\n#### Windows\\n\\n1. Open **Control Panel** → **Network and Internet** → **Network and Sharing Center** → **Change adapter settings**.  \\n2. Right‑click your active connection → **Properties**.  \\n3. Select **Internet Protocol Version 4 (TCP/IPv4)** → **Properties**.  \\n4. Choose **Use the following DNS server addresses** and enter:\\n   - Preferred: `8.8.8.8`\\n   - Alternate: `8.8.4.4`\\n5. Click **OK** and restart your connection.\\n\\n#### macOS\\n\\n1. Go to **System Preferences** → **Network**.  \\n2. Select your active interface → **Advanced** → **DNS** tab.  \\n3. Click the **+** button and add `8.8.8.8` and `8.8.4.4`.  \\n4. Click **OK** → **Apply**.\\n\\n#### Linux (Ubuntu)\\n\\n```bash\\nsudo nano /etc/resolv.conf\\n```\\n\\nAdd:\\n\\n```\\nnameserver 8.8.8.8\\nnameserver 8.8.4.4\\n```\\n\\nSave and exit. (Note: Some distributions use NetworkManager; you can set DNS there.)\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 5. Final Thoughts\\n\\n- **If the public DNS works**, the issue is almost certainly with your ISP’s DNS or your local DNS configuration.  \\n- **If it still doesn’t work**, the problem might be deeper (router firmware, hardware failure, or ISP outage).\\n\\nLet me know which of these steps you’ve tried and what the results were. That will help me guide you further!, please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='f36da877-5142-4e42-bd8c-5202715ccd96'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "not_implemented", "id": ["langchain_ollama", "chat_models", "ChatOllama"], "repr": "ChatOllama(model='gpt-oss:20b', validate_model_on_init=True, temperature=0.0, base_url='http://10.68.186.140:11434')", "name": "ChatOllama"}}
